Is it a managerial revolution or an end to business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees recalls the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to certain "values" from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies of market conquest... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) “requires all parties involved ... to have proactive behavior and a forward-looking view”; this requires a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would be to put employees at the heart of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility.
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In the beginning, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Second, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the ancient behavioral theory that American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread to their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the “commands” (sic) of the commitment of executives, a recent Ipsos investigation published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management position, unsuitable for today’s world.
Identifying and Measuring Mobilization Factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises involves adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists in integrating into all business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined dowry that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their “social performance” and relocate human resource management “on the spot.”
In this way, they create a favorable terrain for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
