The Dinosaur's Cradle
The Tawa hallae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-metre-long, 1.50-metre-high animal running over the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with hip-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Science magazine Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt said.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began a 2006 excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a member of the Utah Museum of Natural History team.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were collected in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, comments Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion currents, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the sauris were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as the "long neck" of the saurisau, and their relatives, the orchivosau, and their relatives.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa findae the researchers found evidence of air bags, such as those that also possess the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa findae also the bones of the spine were obviously partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive air bag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sauropods also possessed air sacs and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers deduce that the sauris first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages were separated at first and spread from South America across all corners of the Earth, which by then still formed a unique land mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa find the remains of two other not very closely related theropods.
The three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study Science.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn palaeontologist Martin Sander.
Their opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare sideline of reptiles to the Mesozoic dominant terrestrial vertebrates remains an enigma.
In the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of present-day crocodiles and pterosaurs and many other saurids.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary to the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, comments Martin Sander.
There may have been a massive extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the contenders in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and international signatories.
Attend professors from the University of Toronto, Cambridge, Vienna or Berkeley, California.
There are teachers from Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
