When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can effortlessly surrender to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, those who experience sleep-like states during wakefulness, or see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are often regarded in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as maniacal.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drug addicts.
Guilt has our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes make the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality blur.
Altered alert states of consciousness may appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, similar processes can be referred to the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Casta<0xC3><0xB1>eda, the states of shamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain has been derailed—especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin, and acetylcholine—and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disrupted.
During a schizophrenic psychosis very often complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of sleep in waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness to the dreamlike states", for Sigmund Freud, sleep was even "a psychosis, with all-purpose forms.
