In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the inside, and fall into a state of overexcitation that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecution.
Especially widespread is hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment, or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the doors to a stream of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the General Psychiatric Clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at it.
At the same time it enters into a passive role, as in a dream, it feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced hallucinations once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, “the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is.”
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations rely on reality, the distancing of experience takes place in reality.
For researchers still an unknown why our brain makes cabriolets.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to lose contact with reality on a temporary basis.
But not all people develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that in addition to genes, there are other determinants.
The researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the brain’s neuronal maturity is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a mother’s viral disease during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains an unknown how that alteration of the neuronal system occurs, which also does not manifest at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a previous disposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmission system.
When the brain heats up
