Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
He approved last year of selectivity and lives with his boyfriend.
A year ago the hallucinations disappeared.
Since he's been in contact over the Internet with psychologist Kasten, he knows he's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art by desperation.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while he begins to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is unoccupied and it takes care of itself to look for entertainment.
Sarah K., the only daughter, had little fear of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he called Dad since he used reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, to those affected like Sarah K. They find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, so they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies nocturnal fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore recommends that his patients appreciate his hallucinations as a special skill.
Boundary situation between sleep and hallucination
in this world too focused on the conscious, imaginary experiences usually get pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in D<0xC3><0xBC>sseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated the so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as being a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that later can not differ from being awake.
Dream-conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis being completely conscious. die bei vollem Bewusssein eine motorische L<0xC3><0xA4>hmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of himself or of the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of its own and imaginary that is detached from reality.
A form of boundary situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change in the world, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way to give meaning and interpretation to an inexhaustible situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich also describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as an action to save the soul.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on several-day trips after a heart valve operation with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen was immersed in a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he was seen lying in bed, an older man on board a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
It was seen in the High Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the Alps with snow firn and met a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later on in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so describe your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intense even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilute the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, onirism, psychosis, hallucinations, and the consumption of narcotics show how fragile the inner reproduction of external reality is, even when we are awake.
Every change in the state of consciousness, says psychologist Kasten, “can lead to a distortion of what we call reality.”
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
