75% of working mothers have had labor problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Women's Fecundity and Labour Trajectory in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working mothers have seen limited employment opportunities due to motherhood.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of cohabitation in couples and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an out-of-home activity, work part-time, or have an unstable job, first start cohabitation with a partner, advance first motherhood, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
“Women aged 35 to 49 with fixed employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their life trajectory to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on motherhood, albeit less on the timing of mating,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that differentiates the age of women by getting married and having the first stem.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the older the age they marry and have the first child.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who have elementary and higher studies have been mothers for the first time at the 25.1 and 32.1 average, respectively.
“There is also another division among women based on their level of study.
While those who have elementary studies get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of middle or higher levels invest this sequence and give priority to getting a stable job as a pre-marriage condition and the arrival of a child,” Delgado explains.
