Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory.
As with ABS anti-lock braking and ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all tourism and light commercial vehicles of new registration, while for the rest a period of absence is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, due to its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant does what it does is to increase the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver's foot.
But he doesn’t always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by the car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance the car uses to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided annually.
The reduction will be even greater – it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided – when so-called intelligent emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects the obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In the event that it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
